<div class="tan-bg">
  <br />
  <h4 class="text-center green">Class Times</h4>
  <p class="text-center"><strong>TUESDAYS, AUGUST 28 - SEPTEMBER 25 @ 6-9PM</strong><br />
  <p class="text-center">REGISTRATION REQUIRED</p>
  <br />
</div>
<br />
<p class="text-center">This is a foundation class that introduces and explores the medium of botanical watercolor, with the focus on plants. Beginning to advanced watercolorists will learn color mixing, how to obtain flat washes, use of glazing applications and an introduction to dry brush technique used by traditional and modern botanical masters, e.g. Redoute', Ehret, Durer, McEwen and Wyeth.</p>

</br>
<h4 class="text-center green">MATERIALS LIST - ARTIST/STUDENT TO PROVIDE</h4>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Transparent Watercolors</strong> - Recommended Winsor Newton Artists’ grade (Not Cotman) - either 5 ml or 14/15 ml size
    <ul>
      <li>Winsor Lemon – (cool)</li>
      <li>Cadmium Yellow Pale –(warm) or Cadmium Yellow - (warm)</li>
      <li>Ultramarine Blue or French Ultramarine Blue - (warm)</li>
      <li>Cerulean Blue - (cool)</li>
      <li>Alizerin Crimson Red - (cool)</li>
      <li>Cadmium Red – (warm)</li>
    </ul>
  </li><br />

  <li><strong>Brushes:</strong> Sceptre Gold recommended for beginners and intermediates: one each – Sceptre Gold II size 2 and 5, or Kolinsky sables: Raphael 8404 Brand: size 1 and 4 or Winsor Newton Series 7 brand: size 2 and 4. Note: Utrecht (Sugarhouse) has Red Sable brushes. Optional but good: "The Masters" brush cleaner, a cake soluble with water.

  </li><br />

  <li><strong>Detail Brush:</strong> A specialty brush you must order online. I use a Dick Blick brand: size 2 Studio Sable, Kolinsky Sable Detail. Also available: size 3 Winsor Newton Miniature Kolinsky Sable. Detail brushes have shorter hairs but are fuller at the ferrule to hold more paint. This brush used in dry brush stage. Excellent detail brush.</li>

  <li><strong>Mixing Brush:</strong> A #3,4,5 inexpensive brush you can use to mix colors with. I use a Loew- Cornell round #4 brush, which I purchased at Michaels for $1.00.</li>

  <li><strong>Pencils:</strong> 2B, HB, 2H 4H – A blue Col-erase pencil will be provided if you do not have it</li>

  <li><strong>Tracing Paper:</strong> 11x14, Canson, Foundation Series, Red, White, and Black cover, AND can be bought locally only at Hobby Lobby for $8 but there is always a 40% coupon available online. This tracing paper is the most translucent of all tracing papers.</li>

  <li><strong>Watercolor Paper:</strong> One pack 11x14 140lb Strathmore Ready Cut Hot Press (6 sheets to a pack). One pack costs $6.37 through Dick Blick online. Utrecht (Sugarhouse) might have it stocked in store. Must be "hot press."</li>

  <li><strong>Other:</strong> Porcelain palette(s): I suggest 7 well Flower Palettes at $5.00 apiece. I suggest an order of 2 from Dick Blick online. There are others you might want in addition.</li>

  <li>Small round or square white china plate for dry brush painting.</li>

  <li>“Pentel Clic” white eraser housed in plastic pen-like housing. Available at Office Stores.</li>

  <li>Small grey kneaded eraser</li>

  <li>Scotch removable tape on Blue plaid card also available at Office Stores</li>

  <li>An eye dropper</li>

  <li>Pencil sharpener electric available in class. Bring handheld as they are easier on pencils</li>

  <li>Small pack or box of KLEENEX or Viva paper towels.</li>

</ul>

<h4 class="text-center green">MATERIALS PROVIDED TO YOU</h4>

<ul>
  <li>One portfolio with watercolor information and exercises (watercolor exercise paper provided)</li>
  <li>Col-Erase 20044 Blue pencil</li>
  <li>Foam board easel</li>
</li>
</ul></br>

<p class="text-center red">All supplies purchased will be used in Botanical Watercolor 2</p>

</br>

